    <ImageBack image="/images/image-background/im-bg.png" altext="main mc back" title="Installing Fabric Mods" />

    <div class="main">
      <h1>Installing Fabric 101</h1>
      <p>Installing fabric is pretty easy. After the tutorial, there will be a link to submit a mod you wanted to be implemented in the server! There will be more info about it.</p>

      <p class="question">Pre-requisite</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Minecraft: Java Edition</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="question">What are the mods we are installing?</p>
      <p>The home page of the website shows the list of mods needed in the server (with optional mods added).</p>

      <h3>Installing</h3>

      <p style="text-align: center;">Click on either one of the boxes to expand the content.<br/><b>NOTE: The CurseForge option is WIP as of now. Looks like it works but is taking me time on doing the steps...</b></p>

      <h4>First time installing mods</h4>

      <details class="tapShow">
        <summary>Manual installation</summary>
        <!-- 0. -->
        <p class="question">0. Install the fabric installer and the zip file.</p>
        <p>Before anything, if you haven't played the recent 1.19.3 update, the Fabric Installer will pop up an error. Launch the game to the recent version and continue on.</p><br>
        <p>Go to the offical <a href="https://fabricmc.net/use/installer/">Fabric website</a> to install the Fabric Installer. And click on the big blue button; it will have you install the installer.</p>
        <img src="/images/install-mods-images/1-install-fabric.png">
        <p>Now we need to install the mods that are dependent to the server. There are two zip files <b>necessary.zip</b> and <b>optional.zip</b>. Click below the buttons to install either one of them.</p>
        <br>
        <p>
        <a href="https://mega.nz/file/jJhjXbzD#b48aLH_lGhYfEmmfZfOjclmm5Srifx92ZSDBgwxKVC8" class="zip-button">necessary.zip</a>
        <a href="https://mega.nz/file/OUA1QCwQ#7vl6Q28bSaRuDq5LpijVaYOjPDvOTbVgKnV4bx57Zpw" class="zip-button">optional.zip</a>
        </p>
        <br>
        <p>The next step we will to, actually, playing the fabric client.</p>

        <hr>
        <!-- 1. -->
        <p class="question">1. Installing Fabric to the Minecraft Launcher</p>
        <p>After the Fabric Installer is downloaded, open the file. It will show something like this:</p>
        <!-- Image here -->
        <img src="/images/install-mods-images/2.1-opening-fabric.png">
        <p>If your in Mac and popped that the file doesn't have a Creator ID, click <a href="#creator-id-warning">here</a></p>

        <p>There are two options on top <code>client</code> and <code>server</code>. We are going to be on <code>client</code> (meaning we are installing the Fabric client to your personal computer). Then we will be doing the most recent version of the server which is <b>1.19.3</b>. Loader version is not important so don't worry about that.</p> <br>
        <p>The last option is selecting your destination for the client to be at. What's on default will be enough so <b>don't touch that</b>.</p><br>
        <p>Have 'create profile' as checked. Meaning that it will create a new client launch for Fabric itself.</p><br>
        <p>And now click the 'Install' button. It should look something like this:</p>
        <img src="/images/install-mods-images/2.2-opening-fabric.png">
        <p>And it will pop-up this message when it's successfully installed into Minecraft:</p>
        <img src="/images/install-mods-images/2.3-opening-fabric.png">
        <p>Now open the Mincraft Launcher and will automatically select something like <code>fabric-loader-'version installed'</code> (bottom left shown the image below).</p>
        <img src="/images/install-mods-images/2.4-opening-fabric.png">
        <p>Press 'play' and when the game opens up the main menu. You can close the game.</p>
        <p>Now it is time to implement the mods!</p>

        <hr>

        <!-- 2. -->
        <p class="question">2. Adding the mods</p>
        <p>You should have the zip file at this point. <b>This step will be demonstrated using <a href="https://www.win-rar.com/start.html?&L=0">WinRar</a></b>. So it will not be the same for everyone (if so, you can losely use this part to setup the mods folder.)</p>
        <p>Open the zip file (or both if you want the optional, we will talk about it in a bit). I recommend to not unzip it. Since there is a much more faster way into transferring the items. The file with have the mods (image below):</p>
        <img src="/images/install-mods-images/3.1-adding-mods.png">
        <p>Now go to your <code>.minecraft</code> folder.</p>
        <br>
        <p>For Windows 10 and 11, do <b>Win + R</b> and when the <code>Run</code> program opens up, type <code>%appdata%</code> on the text input.</p>
        <img src="/images/install-mods-images/3.2-adding-mods.png">
        <p>It will automatically open the <code>AppData</code> folder (tl;dr, the folder with all the apps file). The <code>.minecraft</code> folder will be the first one on the list. And click on that folder.</p>
        <br>
        <p>For Mac OS open <b>Spotlight</b>, and type (mostly copy) this string in the search bar: <code>~/Library/Application Support/minecraft</code>. It will open up the mods folder.</p>
        <img src="/images/install-mods-images/3.3-adding-mods.png">
        <p style="font-size:12px">Image by <i>The Breakdown</i></p>
        <br>
        <p>Now that we are in the <code>.minecraft</code> (or just the <code>minecraft</code> folder in mac) check to see if the <code>mods</code> folder is in <code>.minecraft</code>. It should be added automatically when you've started a Minecraft game with the Fabric version. If not, just simply add the folder just exactly <code>mods</code>.</p><br>
        <p>Now, have the zip file open and drag all the mods to the mods folder. It will automatically "unzip" the file and drag it to the <code>mods</code> folder.</p>
        <img src="/images/install-mods-images/3.4-adding-mods.png">
        <p>If you have the <b>optional.zip</b> folder open. You can drag selected mods you think will be necessary for your needs.</p>
        <br>
        <p>And that's it!</p>

        <hr>

        <p class="question">3. Troubleshooting</p>
        <p>If you every experience any of these crash errors:</p>
        <pre>
         java.lang.RuntimeException
  java.lang.AbstractMethodError</pre>
        <p>It means that <b>you are not in the correct version</b>. Make sure you have installed the correct version of Fabric. The server is on version <b>1.19.3</b>.</p>

        <hr style="background-color: #cfcfcf">

        <a name="creator-id-warning"></a>
        <p><b>For Mac users</b>, if you open up the download file of the Fabric Installer. It will have a pop-up of a warning saying something about a 'Creator ID' or something similar. Here is a simple way to do this (thanks to <a href="https://support.apple.com/guide/mac-help/open-a-mac-app-from-an-unidentified-developer-mh40616/mac">Apple Support</a>).</p> 
        <br>
        <p>It is assumed you have the Java client installed.</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to the folder that has the Fabric Installer file.</li>
          <li><b>Ctrl + Click</b> and hold it to you see the '<b>Open with...</b>'</li>
          <li>And select the <b>Java Application</b> option.</li>
          <li>It will worn you that you are opening a file that does not have a creator ID. There should be a button that say '<b>Open</b>' which it will force open the file.</li>
          <li>Now you can continue on step 1.</li>
        </ol>
      </details>

      <details class="tapShow">
        <summary>With CurseForge</summary>
        <p>WIP</p>
      </details>

      <h4>Adding updated mods</h4>
      <details class="tapShow">
        <summary>Manual Installation</summary>
        <p>Just simply follow step 2 under the <b>First time installing mods</b>. Which is simply installing the mods from the <code>necessary.zip</code>/<code>optional.zip</code> file and dragging it to the <code>mods</code> file.</p>
        <p>Simply install the zip file below (either one that has been officially updated),</p>
        <br>
        <p>
        <a href="https://mega.nz/file/jJhjXbzD#b48aLH_lGhYfEmmfZfOjclmm5Srifx92ZSDBgwxKVC8" class="zip-button">necessary.zip</a>
        <a href="https://mega.nz/file/OUA1QCwQ#7vl6Q28bSaRuDq5LpijVaYOjPDvOTbVgKnV4bx57Zpw" class="zip-button">optional.zip</a>
        </p>
        <br>
        <p>Open the zip file and drag it to the <code>mods</code> file. It will pop-up that there will be some files that might be duplicated. Simply click <b>Skip these files</b> (the second option).</p>
        <img src="/images/install-mods-images/1.1-exmaple-of-many-files-added.png" alt="">
        <p>And that is it!</p>
      </details>

      <details class="tapShow">
        <summary>With CurseForge</summary>
        <p>WIP</p>
      </details>

      <hr>

      <h3>Submit your mod!</h3>
      <p class="question">Fill below to request a mod!</p>
      <form method="post" data-netlify="true" name="implementMod">
        <p><span style="color: red">*</span> Required</p>
        <label>Minecraft IGN<span style="color: red">*</span>: <input type="text" name="mc-ign" required></label><br>
        <label>Mod Name<span style="color: red">*</span>: <input type="text" name="mod-name" required></label><br>
        <label>
          What is the mod type?<span style="color: red">*</span>: 
          <select name="mod-type" required>
            <option value="optimization">Optimization</option>
            <option value="qol">Quality of Life</option>
            <option value="vis-improvement">Visual Improvement</option>
            <option value="general">General Vanilla Approvement</option>
            <option value="other">Other</option>
          </select>
        </label><br>
        <label>If 'other', what type is it?: <input type="text" name="other" id=""></label><br>
        <label>
          Does the mod need dependencies?<span style="color: red">*</span>: 
          <select name="dependencies" required>
            <option value="yes">Yes</option>
            <option value="no">No</option>
          </select>
        </label><br>
        <label>If so, what are they (if more than one, seperate them with commas): <input type="text" name="yes-dependencies" id=""></label><br>
        <label>Mod Link<span style="color: red">*</span>: <input type="url" name="mod-link" required></label><br>
        <button type="submit" id="submit_button">Submit!</button>
      </form>


    </div>


  </body>
</html>
